South Africa and Germany already enjoy 72 bilateral agreements, with South Africa being Germany's largest trading partner in Africa. Courtesy #DStv403 PRETORIA - President Cyril Ramaphosa will host German Chancellor Angela Merkel at the Union buildings on Thursday. The two leaders will also co-chair the South Africa-Germany Business round table. WATCH: Ramaphosa fights CR17 report in court South Africa and Germany already enjoy 72 bilateral agreements, with South Africa being Germany's largest trading partner in Africa. "Approximately 600 German companies are represented in South Africa. Total trade reached R235-billion over the 12 months to the end of November 2019, while South African exports (at R108-billion) exceeded R100-billion for the first time, narrowing the trade deficit," the Presidency said in a statement. Merkel's visit follows the successful state visit by the Head of State of the Federal Republic of Germany President Frank-Walter Steinmeier in Cape Town in November 2018.